'''Tropical Storm Allison''' was a [[tropical cyclone#Intensity classifications|tropical storm]] that devastated southeast [[Texas]] in June of the [[2001 Atlantic hurricane season]]. The first storm of the season, Allison lasted unusually long for a June storm, remaining tropical or subtropical for 15&nbsp;days. The storm developed from a [[tropical wave]] in the northern [[Gulf of Mexico]] on June 4, 2001, and struck the upper Texas coast shortly thereafter. It drifted northward through the state, turned back to the south, and re-entered the Gulf of Mexico. The storm continued to the east-northeast, made landfall on [[Louisiana]], then moved across the southeast United States and [[Mid-Atlantic States|Mid-Atlantic]]. Allison was the first storm since [[Tropical Storm Frances (1998)|Tropical Storm Frances]] in 1998 to strike the northern Texas coastline.<ref name="ivey">{{cite web|author=John P. Ivey|year=2002|title=Flood Safety and Tropical Storm Allison|accessdate=2006-05-15|url=http://www.floodsafety.com/media/pdfs/texas/ivey.pdf|format=PDF}}</ref>

The storm dropped heavy rainfall along its path, peaking at over 40&nbsp;inches (1,000&nbsp;mm) in Texas. The worst flooding occurred in [[Houston]], where most of Allison's damage occurred: 30,000 became homeless after the storm flooded over 70,000&nbsp;houses and destroyed 2,744&nbsp;homes. Downtown Houston was inundated with flooding, causing severe damage to hospitals and businesses. Twenty-three people died in Texas. Along its entire path, Allison caused $5.5 billion ($6.7&nbsp;billion 2008&nbsp;USD) in damage and 41 deaths. Aside from Texas, the places worst hit were Louisiana and southeastern [[Pennsylvania]].

Following the storm, President [[George W. Bush]] designated 75 counties along Allison's path as disaster areas (the first time he had to do so), which enabled the citizens affected to apply for aid. Allison is the only tropical storm to have its name [[List of retired Atlantic hurricane names|retired]] without ever having reached hurricane strength.

==Meteorological history==
{{storm path|Allison 2001 track.png}}
A tropical wave moved off the coast of [[Africa]] on May 21, 2001. It moved westward across the [[Atlantic Ocean]], retaining little convection on its way. After moving across [[South America]] and the southwestern [[Caribbean Sea]], the wave entered the eastern North [[Pacific Ocean]] on June 1. A low-level circulation developed on June 2, while it was about 230&nbsp;miles (370&nbsp;km) south-southeast of [[Salina Cruz]], [[Mexico]]. Southerly flow forced the system northward, and the wave moved inland on June 3. The low-level circulation dissipated, though the mid-level circulation persisted. It emerged into the Gulf of Mexico on June 4, and developed deep convection on its eastern side.<ref name="TCR">{{cite web|author=Stacy R. Stewart|title=Tropical Storm Allison Tropical Cyclone Report|date=February 28, 2001|publisher=National Hurricane Center|accessdate=2008-08-16|url=http://www.nhc.noaa.gov/2001allison.html}}</ref> Early on June 5, satellite imagery suggested that a tropical depression was forming in the northwest Gulf of Mexico, which was furthered by reports of wind gusts as high as 60&nbsp;mph (95&nbsp;km/h) just a few hundred feet above the surface, towards the east side of the system.<ref>{{cite web|author=Stewart|title=June 5 Tropical Weather Outlook|date=June 5, 2001|publisher=National Hurricane Center|accessdate=2008-08-16|url=ftp://ftp.met.fsu.edu/pub/weather/tropical/Outlook-A/2001/Jun/2001060514.ABNT20}}</ref>
[[Image:Tropical Storm Allison- Peak.JPG|right|thumb|Tropical Storm Allison on June 5 at peak strength]]

At 1200&nbsp;UTC on June 5, the disturbance developed a broad, low-level circulation, and was classified as Tropical Storm Allison, the first storm of the [[2001 Atlantic hurricane season]]. Some intensification was projected, though it was expected to be hindered by cool offshore sea surface temperatures.<ref>{{cite web|author=Stewart|title=Tropical Storm Allison Discussion Number 1|date=June 5, 2001|publisher=National Hurricane Center|accessdate=2008-08-16|url=http://www.nhc.noaa.gov/archive/2001/dis/al012001.discus.001.html}}</ref> Due to the cold-core nature of the center, Allison initially contained [[subtropical cyclone|subtropical characteristics]]. Despite this, the storm quickly strengthened to attain peak sustained winds of 60&nbsp;mph (95&nbsp;km/h), with tropical storm-force winds extending up to 230&nbsp;miles (370&nbsp;km) east of the center, and a minimum central pressure of 1000 [[Bar (unit)|mbar]].<ref name="TCR"/> The storm initially moved very little, and the presence of several small vortices from within the deep convection caused difficulty in determining the exact center location.<ref name="disc2">{{cite web|author=Stewart|title=Tropical Storm Allison Discussion Number 2|date=June 5, 2001|url=http://www.nhc.noaa.gov/archive/2001/dis/al012001.discus.002.html|accessdate=2008-08-16|publisher=National Hurricane Center}}</ref>

Later in the day, several different track forecasts arose. One scenario had the cyclone tracking westward in to Mexico. Another projected the storm moving east towards southern Louisiana. At the time, it was noted that little rain or wind persisted near the center, but rather to the north and east.<ref>{{cite web|author=Lawrence|title=Tropical Storm Allison Discussion Number 3|date=June 5, 2001|publisher=National Hurricane Center|accessdate=2008-08-16|url=http://www.nhc.noaa.gov/archive/2001/dis/al012001.discus.003.html}}</ref> Under the steering currents of a subtropical ridge that extended in an east<U+2013>west orientation across the southeast [[United States]],<ref name="disc2"/> Allison weakened while nearing the Texas coastline, and struck near [[Freeport, Texas]] with 50&nbsp;mph (80&nbsp;km/h) winds.<ref name="TCR"/> Inland, the storm rapidly weakened, and the [[National Hurricane Center]] discontinued advisories early on June 6.<ref>{{cite web|author=Pasch|title=Tropical Depression Allison Public Advisory Number 4|date=June 6, 2001|publisher=National Hurricane Center|accessdate=2008-08-16|url=http://www.nhc.noaa.gov/archive/2001/pub/al012001.public.004.html}}</ref> Shortly after being downgraded to a tropical depression, surface observations showed an elongated circulation with a poorly defined center, which had reformed closer to the deep convection.<ref>{{cite web|author=Pasch|title=Tropical Depression Allison Discussion Number 4|date=June 6, 2001|publisher=National Hurricane Center|accessdate=2008-08-16|url=http://www.nhc.noaa.gov/archive/2001/ALLISON.html}}</ref>
[[Image:Tropical Storm Allison- Eye.jpg|left|thumb|Tropical Storm Allison with an [[Eye (cyclone)|eye]]-like feature over Mississippi]]

The depression drifted northward until reaching [[Lufkin, Texas]], where it stalled due to a high pressure system to its north.<ref name="TCR"/>  While stalling over Texas, the storm dropped excessive rainfall, peaking at just over 40&nbsp;inches (1,033&nbsp;mm) in northwestern [[Jefferson County, Texas|Jefferson County]].<ref name="hpc">{{cite web|author=Hydrometeorological Prediction Center|year=2006|title=Rainfall totals from Tropical Storm Allison|accessdate=2006-05-17|url=http://www.hpc.ncep.noaa.gov/tropical/rain/allison2001.html}}</ref>  On June 7, the subtropical ridge off [[Florida]] weakened, while the ridge west of Texas intensified. This steered Tropical Depression Allison to make a clockwise loop, and the storm began drifting to the southwest. As the center reached [[Huntsville, Texas]], a heavy rain band began to back build from Louisiana westward into [[Liberty County, Texas]], which had caused additional flooding.<ref name="synoptic"/> At the time, the system had a minimum central pressure of about 1004&nbsp;mb and maximum sustained winds of about {{convert|10|mph|km/h|abbr=on}}.<ref>{{cite web|author=Pereira|title=Storm Summary Number 12 for the Remnants of Allison|date=June 8, 2001|publisher=Hydrometeorological Prediction Center|accessdate=2008-08-16|url=http://www.hpc.ncep.noaa.gov/tropical2001/allison/06080109.html |archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20061008144835/http://www.hpc.ncep.noaa.gov/tropical2001/allison/06080109.html |archivedate = October 8, 2006}}</ref>

Late on June 9 and early on June 10, Allison's remnants once again reached the Gulf of Mexico and emerged over open waters.<ref>{{cite web|author=Pereira|title=Storm Summary Number 19 for the Remnants of Allison|date=June 8, 2001|publisher=Hydrometeorological Prediction Center|accessdate=2008-08-16|url=http://www.hpc.ncep.noaa.gov/tropical2001/allison/06100103.html |archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20061008144553/http://www.hpc.ncep.noaa.gov/tropical2001/allison/06100103.html |archivedate = October 8, 2006}}</ref> The low once again became nearly stationary about 60&nbsp;mi (100&nbsp;km) south of [[Galveston, Texas]], and despite more favorable upper-level winds, it showed no signs of redevelopment.<ref>{{cite web|author=Stewart|title=June 10 Tropical Weather Outlook|date=June 10, 2001|publisher=National Hurricane Center|accessdate=2008-08-16|url=ftp://ftp.met.fsu.edu/pub/weather/tropical/Outlook-A/2001/Jun/2001061008.ABNT20}}</ref> Due to dry air and moderate westerly [[wind shear]], the storm transformed into a subtropical cyclone. While the subtropical depression moved eastward, a new low level circulation redeveloped to the east, and Allison quickly made landfall on [[Morgan City, Louisiana]] on June 11.<ref name="TCR"/> At around the same time, the surface center reformed to the east-northeast of its previous location, aligning with the mid-level circulation.<ref>{{cite web|author=Clark|title=Storm Summary Number 23 for the Remnants of Tropical Storm Allison|date=June 10, 2001|publisher=Hydrometeorological Prediction Center|accessdate=2008-08-16|url=http://www.hpc.ncep.noaa.gov/tropical2001/allison/06110103.html |archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20061008145134/http://www.hpc.ncep.noaa.gov/tropical2001/allison/06110103.html |archivedate = October 8, 2006}}</ref> Strong [[thunderstorm]]s redeveloped over the circulation, and Allison strengthened into a subtropical storm over southeastern Louisiana.<ref name="TCR"/> The storm intensified further to attain sustained winds of 45&nbsp;mph (70&nbsp;km/h) and a minimum barometric pressure of about 1000&nbsp;mb near Mclain, Mississippi, accompanied by a well-defined [[Eye (cyclone)|eye]]-like feature.<ref>{{cite web|author=Roth & Mcelroy|title=Storm Summary Number 25 for the Former T.S. Allison|date=June 11, 2001|publisher=Hydrometeorological Prediction Center|accessdate=2008-08-16|url=http://www.hpc.ncep.noaa.gov/tropical2001/allison/06110115.html |archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20061008144455/http://www.hpc.ncep.noaa.gov/tropical2001/allison/06110115.html |archivedate = October 8, 2006}}</ref>
[[Image:Tropical Storm Allison- Carolina.gif|right|thumb|Tropical Storm Allison over North Carolina]]

The storm was officially downgraded to a subtropical depression at 0000&nbsp;UTC on June 12. Somewhat accelerating, the depression tracked to the east-northeast through [[Mississippi]], [[Alabama]], [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]], and [[South Carolina]] before becoming nearly stationary near [[Wilmington, North Carolina]].<ref name="TCR"/> The depression drifted through North Carolina and sped to the northeast for a time in response to an approaching cold front.<ref>{{cite web|author=Avila|title=June 14 Tropical Weather Outlook|date=June 14, 2001|publisher=National Hurricane Center|accessdate=2008-08-16|url=ftp://ftp.met.fsu.edu/pub/weather/tropical/Outlook-A/2001/Jun/2001061415.ABNT20}}</ref> Though satellite and radar imagery show the system was well-organized, the system slowed and moved erratically for a period of time,<ref>{{cite web|author=Beven|title=June 14 Tropical Weather Outlook|date=June 14, 2001|publisher=National Hurricane Center|accessdate=2008-08-16|url=ftp://ftp.met.fsu.edu/pub/weather/tropical/Outlook-A/2001/Jun/2001061421.ABNT20}}</ref> executing what appeared to be a small counterclockwise loop.<ref>{{cite web|author=Ziegenfelder & Mcelroy|title=Storm Summary Number 38 for the Remnants of T.S. Allison|date=June 14, 2001|publisher=Hydrometeorological Prediction Center|accessdate=2008-08-16|url=http://www.hpc.ncep.noaa.gov/tropical2001/allison/06140121.html| archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20061008144543/http://www.hpc.ncep.noaa.gov/tropical2001/allison/06140121.html| archivedate = October 8, 2006}}</ref>

The storm began tracking in a generally northeasterly direction, and crossed into the southern [[Delmarva Peninsula]] on June 16.<ref>{{cite web|author=Mcelroy|title=Storm Summary Number 46 for the remnants of Allison|date=June 16, 2001|publisher=Hydrometeorological Prediction Center|accessdate=2008-08-16|url=http://www.hpc.ncep.noaa.gov/tropical2001/allison/06160121.html| archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20061008144750/http://www.hpc.ncep.noaa.gov/tropical2001/allison/06160121.html| archivedate = October 8, 2006}}</ref> The subtropical remnants reached the Atlantic on June 17, and while located east of [[Atlantic City, New Jersey]], winds began to restrengthen, and heavy rains formed to the north of the circulation. The low was interacting with a [[Weather front|frontal boundary]], and started merging with it, as it accelerated to the northeast at {{convert|13|mph|km/h|abbr=on}}.<ref>{{cite web|author=Mcelroy|title=Storm Summary Number 49 for the Remnants of Allison|date=June 17, 2001|publisher=Hydrometeorological Prediction Center|accessdate=2008-08-16|url=http://www.hpc.ncep.noaa.gov/tropical2001/allison/06170115.html| archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20061008144407/http://www.hpc.ncep.noaa.gov/tropical2001/allison/06170115.html| archivedate = October 8, 2006}}</ref> The remnants of Allison briefly reintensified to a [[subtropical cyclone|subtropical storm]] through [[Baroclinity|baroclinic]] processes, though it became [[Extratropical cyclone|extratropical]] while south of [[Long Island]].<ref name="TCR"/> By later on June 17, the low was situated off the coast of [[Rhode Island]], spreading a swath of precipitation over New England.<ref>{{cite web|author=Clark|title=Storm Summary Number 51 for the Remnants of Allison|date=June 17, 2001|publisher=Hydrometeorological Prediction Center|accessdate=2008-08-16|url=http://www.hpc.ncep.noaa.gov/tropical2001/allison/06180103.html| archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20061008145432/http://www.hpc.ncep.noaa.gov/tropical2001/allison/06180103.html| archivedate = October 8, 2006}}</ref> The remnants of the tropical storm were then absorbed by the frontal boundary by June 18, and eventually passed south of [[Cape Race|Cape Race, Newfoundland]] on June 20, where the extratropical cyclone dissipated.<ref name="TCR"/>

==Preparations==
{{main|Effects of Tropical Storm Allison in Texas}}
Shortly after the storm formed, officials in [[Galveston County, Texas]] issued a voluntary evacuation for the western end of [[Galveston Island]], as the area was not protected by the [[Galveston Seawall]].<ref name="TCR"/> The ferry from the island to the [[Bolivar Peninsula]] was closed, while voluntary evacuations were issued in [[Surfside Beach, Texas|Surfside]] in [[Brazoria County, Texas|Brazoria County]].<ref name="nws1">{{cite web|author=Houston/Galveston National Weather Service|year=2001|title=Hurricane Local Statement (1)|accessdate=2006-05-15|url=http://www.srh.noaa.gov/hgx/projects/allison01/textproducts/HLSHOU.1.txt| archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20040930223636/http://www.srh.noaa.gov/hgx/projects/allison01/textproducts/HLSHOU.1.txt| archivedate = September 30, 2004}}</ref> When the [[National Hurricane Center]] issued the first advisory on Allison, officials issued [[Tropical cyclone watches and warnings|Tropical Storm Warnings]] from [[Sargent, Texas]] to [[Morgan City, Louisiana]].<ref name="disc1">{{cite web|author=National Hurricane Center|year=2001|title=Tropical Storm Allison Discussion #1|accessdate=2006-05-15|url=http://www.nhc.noaa.gov/archive/2001/pub/al012001.public.001.html}}</ref> After the storm made landfall, [[flash flood]] watches and warnings were issued for numerous areas in eastern Texas.<ref name="nws3">{{cite web|author=Houston/Galveston National Weather Service|year=2001|title=Hurricane Local Statement (3)|accessdate=2006-05-15|url=http://www.srh.noaa.gov/hgx/projects/allison01/textproducts/HLSHOU.5.txt| archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20060412082319/http://www.srh.noaa.gov/hgx/projects/allison01/textproducts/HLSHOU.5.txt| archivedate = April 12, 2006}}</ref> During the flood event, the National Weather Service in Houston issued 99 flash flood warnings with an average lead time of 40&nbsp;minutes. With an average lead time of 24&nbsp;minutes, the National Weather Service in [[Lake Charles, Louisiana]] issued 47&nbsp;flash flood warnings. With an average lead time of 39&nbsp;minutes, the National Weather Service in New Orleans/Baton Rouge issued 87&nbsp;flash flood warnings, of which 30 were not followed by a flash flood.<ref name="nws">{{cite web|author=United States Department of Commerce|year=2001|title=Tropical Storm Allison Heavy Rains and Floods in Texas and Louisiana|accessdate=2006-05-15|url=http://www.nws.noaa.gov/om/assessments/pdfs/allison.pdf|format=PDF}}</ref>

In [[Tallahassee, Florida]], a shelter opened the day prior to Allison's movement northward through the area, seven staff members housing 12&nbsp;people. Two other shelters were on standby. Teams informed citizens in the [[Florida Panhandle]] of flood dangers.<ref name="flalpre">{{cite web|author=United States Red Cross|year=2001|title=Tropical Storm Allison Florida Situation Report|accessdate=2006-05-18|url=http://redcross.tallytown.com/situation/allison-01.pdf|format=PDF|accessdate=2007-12-17}}</ref>

==Impact==
