Tropical Storm Allison was a major flood disaster throughout its path from Texas to the Mid-Atlantic. The worst of the flooding occurred in [[Houston]], Texas, where over 35&nbsp;inches (890&nbsp;mm) of rain fell. Allison killed 41&nbsp;people, of which 27 drowned. The storm also caused over $5&nbsp;billion in damage (2001&nbsp;USD, $6.4&nbsp;billion 2007&nbsp;USD), making Allison the deadliest and costliest tropical storm on record in the United States.<ref name="TCR"/>

===Texas===
{{main|Effects of Tropical Storm Allison in Texas}}
Combined with waves on top, areas of Galveston Island experienced a wall of water 8&nbsp;feet (2.5&nbsp;m) in height, creating [[overwash]] along the coastline. The storm caused winds of up to 43&nbsp;mph (69&nbsp;km/h) at the Galveston Pier. While Allison was stalling over Texas, it dropped very heavy rainfall across the state.<ref name="TCR"/> Minimal beach erosion was reported.<ref name="hogaprelim">{{cite web|author=Houston/Galveston National Weather Service|year=2001|title=Preliminary Report (Houston/Galveston)|accessdate=2006-05-17|url=http://www.srh.noaa.gov/hgx/projects/allison01/textproducts/SATPSHHOU.txt| archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20040207235501/http://www.srh.noaa.gov/hgx/projects/allison01/textproducts/SATPSHHOU.txt| archivedate = February 7, 2004}}</ref> Flash flooding continued for days,<ref name="synoptic">{{cite web|author=Houston/Galveston National Weather Service (Synoptic Situation)|year=2006|title=Tropical Storm Allison Floods, June 5<U+2013>9, 2001|accessdate=2006-05-17|url=http://www.srh.noaa.gov/hgx/projects/allison01/synoptic.htm| archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20041214204857/http://www.srh.noaa.gov/hgx/projects/allison01/synoptic.htm| archivedate = December 14, 2004}}</ref> with rainfall amounts across the state peaking at just over 40&nbsp;inches (1,033&nbsp;mm) in northwestern [[Jefferson County, Texas|Jefferson County]]. In the [[Port of Houston]], a total of 36.99&nbsp;inches (940&nbsp;mm) was reported.<ref name="hpc"/> Houston experienced torrential rainfall in a short amount of time.  The six-day rainfall in Houston amounted to 38.6&nbsp;inches (980&nbsp;mm).<ref name="rms">{{cite web|author=Risk Management Solutions|year=2001|title=Tropical Storm Allison Event Report|accessdate=2006-05-18|url=http://www.rms.com/Publications/TS_Allison.pdf|format=PDF}}</ref> The deluge of rainfall flooded 95,000&nbsp;automobiles and 73,000&nbsp;houses throughout Harris County.<ref name="ivey"/> Tropical Storm Allison destroyed 2,744&nbsp;homes, leaving 30,000&nbsp;homeless with residential damages totaling to $1.76&nbsp;billion (2001&nbsp;USD, $2.05&nbsp;billion 2007&nbsp;USD).<ref name="rms"/>

[[Image:TS Allison Texas flooding.jpg|right|thumb|The Southwest Freeway, near Downtown Houston, lies under water due to flooding from Tropical Storm Allison]]

Several hospitals in the [[Texas Medical Center]], the largest medical complex in the world, experienced severe damage from the storm, which hit quickly and with unexpected fury on a Friday evening. The [[Baylor College of Medicine]] experienced major damage, totaling $495&nbsp;million (2001&nbsp;USD, $577&nbsp;million 2007&nbsp;USD). The medical school lost 90,000&nbsp;research animals, 60,000&nbsp;tumor samples, and 25&nbsp;years of research data. [[The University of Texas Health Science Center at Houston]], across the street, lost thousands of laboratory animals. Throughout the Medical Center, damage totaled to over $2&nbsp;billion (2001&nbsp;USD, $2.3&nbsp;billion 2007&nbsp;USD).<ref name="rms"/>

[[Image:Allison Flood Houston.jpg|thumb|left|[[Buffalo Bayou]] and [[White Oak Bayou]] at Main Street after Tropical Storm Allison hit [[Houston]]]]
The [[Houston Downtown Tunnel System|underground tunnel system]], which connects most large office buildings in downtown Houston, was submerged, as were many streets and parking garages adjacent to [[Buffalo Bayou]]. At the Theatre District, also in downtown, the Houston Symphony, Houston Grand Opera, and Alley Theater lost millions of dollars of costumes, musical instruments, sheet music, archives and other artifacts. By midnight on June 9 nearly every freeway and major road in the city was under several feet of water, forcing hundreds of motorists to abandon their vehicles for higher ground.<ref name="rms"/>

Despite massive flooding damage to entire neighborhoods there were no drowning deaths in flooded homes. In the area, there were twelve&nbsp;deaths from driving, six from walking, three from electrocution, and one in an elevator.<ref name="ivey"/> Elsewhere in Texas, a man drowned when swimming in a ditch in [[Mauriceville, Texas|Mauriceville]].<ref name="nws"/> Damage totaled to $5.2&nbsp;billion (2001&nbsp;USD, $6&nbsp;billion 2007&nbsp;USD) throughout Texas.<ref name="texasdamage">{{cite web|author=National Climatic Data Center|year=2001|title=Event Report for Texas|accessdate=2006-06-07|url=http://www4.ncdc.noaa.gov/cgi-win/wwcgi.dll?wwevent~ShowEvent~450007}}</ref>

===Louisiana===
[[Image:TS Allison-LA.jpg|thumb|right|Flooding in [[Chackbay, Louisiana]]]]
While making its first landfall, Allison's large circulation dropped severe rains on southwest Louisiana.<ref name="nws2">{{cite web|author=Lake Charles National Weather Service|year=2001|title=Hurricane Local Statement (2)|accessdate=2006-05-15|url=http://www.srh.noaa.gov/hgx/projects/allison01/textproducts/NEWPSHLCH.1.txt| archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20040207235525/http://www.srh.noaa.gov/hgx/projects/allison01/textproducts/NEWPSHLCH.1.txt| archivedate = February 7, 2004}}</ref>  Days later, Allison hit the state as a [[subtropical cyclone|subtropical storm]], dropping more heavy rains to the area. Rainfall totals peaked at 29.86&nbsp;inches (758&nbsp;mm) in [[Thibodaux, Louisiana|Thibodaux]], the highest rainfall total in Louisiana from a tropical cyclone since another [[Tropical Storm Allison (1989)|Tropical Storm Allison]] in 1989.<ref name="summary">{{cite web|author=[[David M. Roth]]|year=2001|title=HPC Storm Summary #52 for T.D. Allison|accessdate=2006-05-26|url=http://www.hpc.ncep.noaa.gov/tropical2001/allison/06190109.html| archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20040827200925/http://www.hpc.ncep.noaa.gov/tropical2001/allison/06190109.html| archivedate = August 27, 2004}}</ref> Most of the southeastern portion of the state experienced over 10&nbsp;inches of rain (255&nbsp;mm).<ref name="hpc"/> Winds were generally light, peaking at 38&nbsp;mph (61&nbsp;km/h) sustained in [[Lakefront, Louisiana|Lakefront]] with gusts to 53&nbsp;mph (85&nbsp;km/h) in [[Bay Gardene, Louisiana|Bay Gardene]]. The storm produced a storm surge of 2.5&nbsp;feet (0.75&nbsp;m) in [[Cameron, Louisiana|Cameron]] as it was making landfall in Texas.<ref name="TCR"/> While moving northward through Texas, the outer bands of the storm produced an [[Fujita scale|F1]] [[tornado]] near [[Zachary, Louisiana|Zachary]], damaging several trees and a power line. A man was killed when a damaged power line hit his truck.<ref name="latorn">{{cite web|author=National Climatic Data Center|year=2001|title=Event Report For Louisiana|accessdate=2006-06-02|url=http://www4.ncdc.noaa.gov/cgi-win/wwcgi.dll?wwevent~ShowEvent~432467}}</ref>

When Allison first made landfall, heavy rainfall flooded numerous houses and businesses. Minor wind gusts caused minor roof damage to 10&nbsp;houses in [[Cameron Parish, Louisiana|Cameron Parish]], while its storm surge flooded portions of [[Louisiana Highway 82]].<ref name="ladam">{{cite web|author=National Climatic Data Center|year=2001|title=Event Report for Louisiana 2|accessdate=2006-06-02|url=http://www4.ncdc.noaa.gov/cgi-win/wwcgi.dll?wwevent~ShowEvent~432482}}</ref> When the system returned, more rainfall occurred, flooding over 1,000&nbsp;houses in [[Saint Tammany Parish, Louisiana|St. Tammany Parish]],<ref name="ladam2">{{cite web|author=National Climatic Data Center|year=2001|title=Event Report For Louisiana 3|accessdate=2006-06-02|url=http://www4.ncdc.noaa.gov/cgi-win/wwcgi.dll?wwevent~ShowEvent~432494}}</ref> 80 houses in [[Saint Bernard Parish, Louisiana|Saint Bernard Parish]],<ref name="ladam3">{{cite web|author=National Climatic Data Center|year=2001|title=Event Report for Louisiana 4|accessdate=2006-06-02|url=http://www4.ncdc.noaa.gov/cgi-win/wwcgi.dll?wwevent~ShowEvent~432495}}</ref> and hundreds of houses elsewhere in the state. The flooding also forced 1,800&nbsp;residents from their homes in [[East Baton Rouge Parish, Louisiana|East Baton Rouge Parish]].<ref name="ladam4">{{cite web|author=National Climatic Data Center|year=2001|title=Event Report for Louisiana 5|accessdate=2006-06-02|url=http://www4.ncdc.noaa.gov/cgi-win/wwcgi.dll?wwevent~ShowEvent~432484}}</ref> The deluge left numerous roads impassable, while runoff resulted in severe river flooding. The [[Bogue Falaya River]] in [[Covington, Louisiana|Covington]] crested past its peak twice to near record levels.<ref name="ladam2"/> The [[Amite River|Amite]] and [[Comite River]]s reached their highest levels since 1983. In addition, the levee along the [[Bayou Manchac]] broke, flooding roadways and more houses.<ref name="ladam4"/> Damage in Louisiana totaled to $65&nbsp;million (2001&nbsp;USD, $75&nbsp;million 2007&nbsp;USD).<ref name="rms"/>

===Southeast United States===
[[Image:Allison2001rain.gif|thumb|right|Rainfall totals from Allison]]
In [[Mississippi]], Allison produced heavy rainfall of over 10&nbsp;inches (255&nbsp;mm) in one night,<ref name="msdam">{{cite web|author=National Climatic Data Center|year=2001|title=Event Report for Mississippi|accessdate=2006-06-06|url=http://www4.ncdc.noaa.gov/cgi-win/wwcgi.dll?wwevent~ShowEvent~436002}}</ref> while some areas in the southwestern portion of the state received over 15&nbsp;inches (380&nbsp;mm).<ref name="hpc"/> The flooding damaged numerous houses and flooded many roadways.<ref name="msdam"/> Thunderstorms from the storm produced four tornadoes,<ref name="TCR"/> including one in [[Gulfport, Mississippi]] that damaged 10 houses.<ref name="mstorn">{{cite web|author=National Climatic Data Center|year=2001|title=Event Report for Mississippi (2)|accessdate=2006-06-06|url=http://www4.ncdc.noaa.gov/cgi-win/wwcgi.dll?wwevent~ShowEvent~436004}}</ref> Severe thunderstorms in [[George County, Mississippi|George County]] damaged 15 houses, destroyed 10, and injured five people.<ref name="msthun">{{cite web|author=National Climatic Data Center|year=2001|title=Event Report for Mississippi (3)|accessdate=2006-06-06|url=http://www4.ncdc.noaa.gov/cgi-win/wwcgi.dll?wwevent~ShowEvent~436012}}</ref> Damage in Mississippi totaled to over $1&nbsp;million (2001&nbsp;USD, $1.2&nbsp;million 2007&nbsp;USD).<ref name="msdam"/><ref name="mstorn"/><ref name="msthun"/> Rainfall in [[Alabama]] was moderate, with areas near [[Mobile, Alabama|Mobile]] experiencing more than 10&nbsp;inches (255&nbsp;mm).<ref name="hpc"/> Heavy rainfall closed several roads in [[Crenshaw County, Alabama|Crenshaw County]].<ref name="aldam">{{cite web|author=National Climatic Data Center|year=2001|title=Event Report for Alabama|accessdate=2006-06-07|url=http://www4.ncdc.noaa.gov/cgi-win/wwcgi.dll?wwevent~ShowEvent~419596}}</ref> The storm, combined with a high pressure, produced coastal flooding in southern Alabama.<ref name="aldam2">{{cite web|author=National Climatic Data Center|year=2001|title=Event Report for Alabama (2)|accessdate=2006-06-07|url=http://www4.ncdc.noaa.gov/cgi-win/wwcgi.dll?wwevent~ShowEvent~419592}}</ref> Allison produced an [[Fujita scale|F0]] tornado in southwest [[Mobile County, Alabama|Mobile County]] that caused minor roof damage<ref name="altorn2">{{cite web|author=National Climatic Data Center|year=2001|title=Event Report for Alabama (3)|accessdate=2006-06-07|url=http://www4.ncdc.noaa.gov/cgi-win/wwcgi.dll?wwevent~ShowEvent~419588}}</ref> and another F0 tornado in [[Covington County, Alabama|Covington County]] that caused minor damage to six homes and a church.<ref name="altorn2"/>

The storm, combined with a high pressure system, produced a strong pressure gradient, resulting in strong rip currents off the coast of [[Florida]]. The currents prompted sirens, which are normally used for storm warnings, to be activated in [[Pensacola Beach, Florida|Pensacola Beach]].<ref name="flrip">{{cite web|author=National Climatic Data Center|year=2001|title=Event Report for Florida|accessdate=2006-06-07|url=http://www4.ncdc.noaa.gov/cgi-win/wwcgi.dll?wwevent~ShowEvent~423536}}</ref> The rip currents killed 5 off the coast of Florida.<ref name="flrip2">{{cite web|author=National Climatic Data Center|year=2001|title=Event Report for Florida (2)|accessdate=2006-06-07|url=http://www4.ncdc.noaa.gov/cgi-win/wwcgi.dll?wwevent~ShowEvent~423543}}</ref> Outer rain bands from the storm dropped heavy rainfall across the [[Florida Panhandle]] of over 11&nbsp;inches (280&nbsp;mm) in one day. The [[Tallahassee Regional Airport]] recorded 10.13&nbsp;inches (257&nbsp;mm) in 24&nbsp;hours, breaking the old 24&nbsp;hour record set in 1969.<ref name="fldam">{{cite web|author=National Climatic Data Center|year=2001|title=Event Report for Florida (3)|accessdate=2006-06-07|url=http://www4.ncdc.noaa.gov/cgi-win/wwcgi.dll?wwevent~ShowEvent~423575}}</ref> Throughout the state, Allison destroyed 10&nbsp;homes and damaged 599, 196 severely, primarily in [[Leon County, Florida|Leon County]].<ref name="fladam">{{cite web|author=Gathana Parmenas|year=2001|title=Detailed Damage Assessment Summary in Florida|accessdate=2006-05-18|url=http://redcross.tallytown.com/situation/allison-da.xls}}</ref> Including the deaths from rip currents, Allison killed eight people in Florida<ref name="TCR"/> and caused $20&nbsp;million (2001&nbsp;USD, $23&nbsp;million 2007&nbsp;USD) in damage.<ref name="fldam"/>

Over [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]], the storm dropped heavy rainfall of 10&nbsp;inches (255&nbsp;mm) in 24&nbsp;hours in various locations. The deluge caused rivers to crest past their banks, including the [[Oconee River]] at [[Milledgeville, Georgia|Milledgeville]] which peaked at 33.7&nbsp;feet (10.3&nbsp;m). The rainfall, which was heaviest across the southwestern portion of the state, washed out several bridges and roads, and flooded many other roads. Georgia governor [[Roy Barnes]] declared a state of emergency for seven counties in the state.<ref name="gadam">{{cite web|author=National Climatic Data Center|year=2001|title=Event Report for Georgia|accessdate=2006-06-08|url=http://www4.ncdc.noaa.gov/cgi-win/wwcgi.dll?wwevent~ShowEvent~424563}}</ref> The storm also spawned two tornadoes.<ref name="TCR"/> In [[South Carolina]], Allison's outer bands produced 10&nbsp;[[tornado]]es<ref name="TCR"/> and several funnel clouds, though most only caused minor damage limited to a damaged courthouse, snapped trees<ref name="sctorn">{{cite web|author=National Climatic Data Center|year=2001|title=Event Report for South Carolina|accessdate=2006-06-08|url=http://www4.ncdc.noaa.gov/cgi-win/wwcgi.dll?wwevent~ShowEvent~446450}}</ref> and downed power lines.<ref name="sctorn2">{{cite web|author=National Climatic Data Center|year=2001|title=Event Report for South Carolina (2)|accessdate=2006-06-08|url=http://www4.ncdc.noaa.gov/cgi-win/wwcgi.dll?wwevent~ShowEvent~446449}}</ref> Allison produced from 12 to 16&nbsp;inches (305 to 406&nbsp;mm) of rainfall in [[North Carolina]], closing nearly all roads in [[Martin County, North Carolina|Martin County]] and damaging 25&nbsp;homes.<ref name="ncdam">{{cite web|author=National Climatic Data Center|year=2001|title=Event Report for North Carolina|accessdate=2006-06-08|url=http://www4.ncdc.noaa.gov/cgi-win/wwcgi.dll?wwevent~ShowEvent~441768}}</ref> The severe flooding washed out a bridge in eastern [[Halifax County, North Carolina|Halifax County]]<ref name="ncdam2">{{cite web|author=National Climatic Data Center|year=2001|title=Event Report for North Carolina|accessdate=2006-06-08|url=http://www4.ncdc.noaa.gov/cgi-win/wwcgi.dll?wwevent~ShowEvent~441767}}</ref> and flooded numerous cars.<ref name="summary"/> Wet roads caused nine traffic accidents throughout the state.<ref name="TCR"/>

===Mid-Atlantic and Northeast United States===
[[Image:TS Allison-PA.JPG|right|thumb|Damage from flooding in [[Pennsylvania]]]]
In [[Virginia]], Allison produced light rainfall, with the southeastern and south-central portions of the state experiencing over 3&nbsp;inches (76&nbsp;mm).<ref name="hpc"/> A tree in a saturated ground fell over and killed one person.<ref name="usa">{{cite news|author=USA Today.com|year=2001|title=Allison was weak, but a killer|accessdate=2006-06-02|url=http://www.usatoday.com/weather/hurricane/2001/atlantic/allison-final-story.htm | date=2001-07-03}}</ref> Allison also produced one tornado in the state.<ref name="TCR"/> [[Washington, D.C.]] experienced moderate rainfall from the storm, totaling to 2.59&nbsp;inches (66&nbsp;mm) in [[Georgetown, Washington, D.C.|Georgetown]].<ref name="dcrain">{{cite web|author=National Climatic Data Center|year=2001|title=Event Record Details for Tropical Storm Allison in Washington D.C.|accessdate=2006-05-26|url=http://www4.ncdc.noaa.gov/cgi-win/wwcgi.dll?wwevent~ShowEvent~423209}}</ref> In [[Maryland]], rainfall from Tropical Depression Allison totaled to 7.5&nbsp;inches (190&nbsp;mm) in [[Denton, Maryland|Denton]], closing eleven roads and causing washouts on 41 others. The [[Maryland Eastern Shore]] experienced only minor rainfall from one to two inches (25 to 50&nbsp;mm). Damage was light, and no deaths were reported.<ref name="maryall">{{cite web|author=National Climatic Data Center|year=2001|title=Event Record Details for Tropical Storm Allison in Maryland|accessdate=2006-05-26|url=http://www4.ncdc.noaa.gov/cgi-win/wwcgi.dll?wwevent~ShowEvent~433132}}</ref> In [[Delaware]], the storm produced moderate rainfall, peaking at 4.2&nbsp;inches (106&nbsp;mm) in [[Greenwood, Delaware|Greenwood]]. No damage was reported.<ref name="delall">{{cite web|author=National Climatic Data Center|year=2001|title=Event Record Details for Tropical Storm Allison in Delaware|accessdate=2006-05-26|url=http://www4.ncdc.noaa.gov/cgi-win/wwcgi.dll?wwevent~ShowEvent~423153}}</ref>

Allison, in combination with an approaching frontal boundary, dropped heavy rainfall across southeastern Pennsylvania, peaking at 10.17&nbsp;inches (258&nbsp;mm) in [[Chalfont, Pennsylvania|Chalfont]] in [[Bucks County, Pennsylvania|Bucks County]] and over 3&nbsp;inches (76&nbsp;mm) in portions of [[Philadelphia]]. The rainfall caused rivers to rise, with the [[Neshaminy Creek]] in [[Langhorne, Pennsylvania|Langhorne]] peaking at {{convert|16.87|ft|m|1}}. Several other rivers and creeks in southeastern Pennsylvania crested at over 10&nbsp;feet (3&nbsp;m). The rainfall downed numerous weak trees and power lines, leaving 70,000 without power during the storm. The flooding washed out several roads and bridges, including a few [[SEPTA]] rail lines. In addition, the rainfall destroyed 241&nbsp;homes and damaged 1,386 others. Flooding at a [[Dodge]] dealership totaled 150&nbsp;vehicles. Hundreds of people were forced to be rescued from damaged buildings from flood waters. The flooding dislodged a clothes dryer in the basement of the "A" building of the Village Green Apartment Complex in [[Upper Moreland Township, Pennsylvania|Upper Moreland Township]], breaking a natural gas line. The gas leak resulted in an explosion and an ensuing fire that killed six people. Firefighters were unable to render assistance as the building was completely surrounded by floodwaters. Additionally, one man drowned in his vehicle in a river.<ref name="penndam">{{cite web|author=National Climatic Data Center|year=2001|title=Event Record Details for Tropical Storm Allison in Pennsylvania|accessdate=2006-05-26|url=http://www4.ncdc.noaa.gov/cgi-win/wwcgi.dll?wwevent~ShowEvent~445815}}</ref> Damage in Pennsylvania totaled to $215&nbsp;million (2001&nbsp;USD, $250&nbsp;million 2007&nbsp;USD).<ref name="rms"/>

In [[New Jersey]], the storm produced heavy rainfall, peaking at 8.1&nbsp;inches (205&nbsp;mm) in [[Tuckerton, New Jersey|Tuckerton]]. The rains also caused river flooding, including the north branch of the [[Metedeconk River]] in [[Lakewood, New Jersey|Lakewood]] which crested at 8&nbsp;feet (2.5&nbsp;m). The flooding, severe at places, closed several roads, including numerous state highways.<ref name="njdam">{{cite web|author=National Climatic Data Center|year=2001|title=Event Record Details for Tropical Storm Allison in New Jersey|accessdate=2006-05-26|url=http://www4.ncdc.noaa.gov/cgi-win/wwcgi.dll?wwevent~ShowEvent~440625}}</ref> Gusty winds of up to 44&nbsp;mph (71&nbsp;km/h) in [[Atlantic City, New Jersey|Atlantic City]] downed weak trees and power lines, leaving over 13,000 without power. Several people had to be rescued from high waters, though no fatalities occurred in the state. Overall damage was minimal.<ref name="njdam2">{{cite web|author=National Climatic Data Center|year=2001|title=Event Record Details for Tropical Storm Allison in New Jersey|accessdate=2006-05-26|url=http://www4.ncdc.noaa.gov/cgi-win/wwcgi.dll?wwevent~ShowEvent~440624}}</ref>

Tropical Storm Allison caused flash flooding in [[New York]], dropping up to 3&nbsp;inches (75&nbsp;mm) of rain in one hour in several locations and peaking at 5.73&nbsp;inches (146&nbsp;mm) in [[Granite Springs, New York|Granite Springs]]. The rains also caused river flooding, including the [[Mahwah River]] which crested at {{convert|3.79|ft|m|1}}. Allison's rainfall damaged 24 houses and several stores, while the flooding closed several major highways in the [[New York City]] area. Overall damage was light, and no fatalities occurred in New York due to Allison.<ref name="nydam">{{cite web|author=National Climatic Data Center|year=2001|title=Event Record Details for Tropical Storm Allison in New York|accessdate=2006-05-26|url=http://www4.ncdc.noaa.gov/cgi-win/wwcgi.dll?wwevent~ShowEvent~441144}}</ref> Similarly, rainfall in [[Connecticut]] peaked at 7.2&nbsp;inches (183&nbsp;mm) in [[Pomfret, Connecticut|Pomfret]],<ref name="condam2">{{cite web|author=National Climatic Data Center|year=2001|title=Event Record Details for Tropical Storm Allison in Connecticut|accessdate=2006-05-26|url=http://www4.ncdc.noaa.gov/cgi-win/wwcgi.dll?wwevent~ShowEvent~423074}}</ref> closing several roads and causing minor damage to numerous houses. The [[Yantic River]] at [[Yantic, Connecticut|Yantic]] crested at 11.1&nbsp;feet (3.4&nbsp;m),<ref name="condam2"/> while a state road was closed when a private dam in [[Hampton, Connecticut|Hampton]] failed from the rainfall.<ref name="condam2"/> In [[Rhode Island]], Allison produced up to 7.1&nbsp;inches (180&nbsp;mm) of rainfall in [[North Smithfield, Rhode Island|North Smithfield]], washing out several roads and houses, and destroying a log house in [[Foster, Rhode Island|Foster]].<ref name="condam">{{cite web|author=National Climatic Data Center|year=2001|title=Event Record Details for Tropical Storm Allison in Rhode Island|accessdate=2006-05-26|url=http://www4.ncdc.noaa.gov/cgi-win/wwcgi.dll?wwevent~ShowEvent~446298}}</ref>

An isolated severe thunderstorm in the outer bands of Allison produced an [[Fujita scale|F1]] [[tornado]] in [[Worcester County, Massachusetts|Worcester]] and [[Middlesex County, Massachusetts|Middlesex Counties]] in [[Massachusetts]], impacting over 100&nbsp;trees and damaging one house and one small camper. A [[microburst]] in [[Leominster, Massachusetts|Leominster]] and another in [[Shirley, Massachusetts|Shirley]] damaged several trees. Lightning from the storm hit two houses, causing significant damage there but little elsewhere. Allison also produced moderate rainfall in the state, mainly ranging from 3 to 5&nbsp;inches (75 to 125&nbsp;mm). The rainfall caused drainage and traffic problems. Damage in Massachusetts totaled to $400,000 (2001&nbsp;USD, $466,000 2007&nbsp;USD).<ref name="madam">{{cite web|author=National Climatic Data Center|year=2001|title=Event Record Details for Tropical Storm Allison in Massachusetts|accessdate=2006-05-31|url=http://www4.ncdc.noaa.gov/cgi-win/wwcgi.dll?wwevent~ShowEvent~433376}}</ref>

==Aftermath==
{{main|Effects of Tropical Storm Allison in Texas}}
Within weeks of the disaster, [[President of the United States|President]] [[George W. Bush]] declared 75&nbsp;counties in Texas,<ref name="txdeclar">{{cite web|author=FEMA|year=2001|title=Texas Severe Storms & Flooding|accessdate=2006-06-13|url=http://www.fema.gov/news/newsrelease.fema?id=6438}}</ref> southern [[Louisiana]],<ref name="ladeclar">{{cite web|author=Fema|year=2001|title=Louisiana Tropical Storm Allison|accessdate=2006-06-11|url=http://www.fema.gov/news/event.fema?id=116}}</ref> southern [[Mississippi]],<ref name="msdeclar">{{cite web|author=FEMA|year=2001|title=Mississippi Tropical Storm Allison|accessdate=2006-06-11|url=http://www.fema.gov/news/event.fema?id=118}}</ref> northwestern [[Florida]],<ref name="fldeclar">{{cite web|author=FEMA|year=2001|title=Florida Tropical Storm Allison|accessdate=2006-06-11|url=http://www.fema.gov/news/event.fema?id=117}}</ref> and southeastern Pennsylvania as disaster areas.<ref name="padeclar">{{cite web|author=FEMA|year=2001|title=Pennsylvania Tropical Storm Allison|accessdate=2006-06-11|url=http://www.fema.gov/news/event.fema?id=119}}</ref> The declarations allowed affected citizens to receive aid for temporary housing, emergency home repairs, and other serious disaster-related expenses. The [[Federal Emergency Management Agency]] (FEMA) also provided 75% for the cost of debris removal, emergency services related to the disaster, and repairing or replacing damaged public facilities, such as roads, bridges and utilities.<ref name="txdeclar"/>

[[Image:Allison- Red Cross.jpg|right|thumb|Aid from the [[American Red Cross]]]]
A few weeks after Allison, FEMA opened six disaster recovery centers across southeast Texas, which provided recovery information to those who applied for disaster assistance.<ref name="txdrc">{{cite web|author=FEMA|year=2001|title=Disaster Recovery Centers To Open|accessdate=2006-06-14|url=http://www.fema.gov/news/newsrelease.fema?id=6430}}</ref> The [[American Red Cross]] and the [[Salvation Army]] opened 48&nbsp;shelters at the peak of need for people driven from their homes, which served nearly 300,000&nbsp;meals. The [[National Disaster Medical System]] deployed a temporary hospital to Houston with 88 professionals, aiding nearly 500&nbsp;people.<ref name="txhos">{{cite web|author=FEMA|year=2001|title=Mobile Military Hospital Provides Emergency Care For Houston's Citizens|url=http://www.fema.gov/news/newsrelease.fema?id=6410}}</ref> Thirty-five volunteer services provided aid for the flood victims in Texas, including food, clothing, and volunteers to help repair the houses.<ref name="txvol">{{cite web|author=FEMA|year=2001|title=Quiet Heroes&nbsp;<U+2014> Voluntary Agencies|accessdate=2006-06-14|url=http://www.fema.gov/news/newsrelease.fema?id=6395}}</ref> After nearly 50,000&nbsp;cars were flooded and ruined, many people attempted to sell the cars across the country without telling of the car's history.<ref name="txcar">{{cite web|author=FEMA|year=2001|title=Buyer Beware: Flood-Damaged Cars Being Sold|accessdate=2006-06-14|url=http://www.fema.gov/news/newsrelease.fema?id=6395}}</ref> Following the extreme flooding, a [[mosquito]] outbreak occurred, though FEMA provided aid to control the problem.<ref name="txmosq">{{cite web|author=FEMA|year=2001|title=FEMA Funding Mosquito Control|accessdate=2006-06-14|url=http://www.fema.gov/news/newsrelease.fema?id=6412}}</ref> By six months after the storm, around 120,000 Texas citizens applied for federal disaster aid, totaling to $1.05&nbsp;billion (2001&nbsp;USD, $1.22&nbsp;billion 2007&nbsp;USD).<ref name="txaid">{{cite web|author=FEMA|year=2001|title=Six Months After Allison, Disaster Assistance Reaches $1.05&nbsp;Billion|accessdate=2006-06-14|url=http://www.fema.gov/news/newsrelease.fema?id=6219}}</ref>

Like in Texas, a mosquito outbreak occurred in Louisiana. Only pesticides acceptable to the [[United States Environmental Protection Agency|US Environmental Protection Agency]] and the [[United States Fish and Wildlife Service|US Fish and Wildlife Service]] were allowed to be used.<ref name="lamos">{{cite web|author=FEMA|year=2001|title=Responsible Response to Mosquitoes|accessdate=2006-06-14|url=http://www.fema.gov/news/newsrelease.fema?id=6129}}</ref> FEMA officials warned homeowners of the dangers of floodwaters, including mold, mildew, and bacteria.<ref name="lacl">{{cite web|author=FEMA|year=2001|title=Drying Out, Cleaning Up After Allison|accessdate=2006-06-14|url=http://www.fema.gov/news/newsrelease.fema?id=6128}}</ref> By three months after the storm, just under 100,000 Louisiana citizens applied for federal aid, totaling to over $110&nbsp;million (2001&nbsp;USD, $128&nbsp;million 2007&nbsp;USD). $25&nbsp;million (2001&nbsp;USD, $29&nbsp;million 2007&nbsp;USD) of the total was for business loans, while an additional $8&nbsp;million was for public assistance for communities and state agencies.<ref name="laidsum">{{cite web|author=FEMA|year=2001|title=Summary Of Louisiana Disaster Assistance|accessdate=2006-06-14|url=http://www.fema.gov/news/newsrelease.fema?id=6049}}</ref> More than 750 flood victims in [[Florida]] applied for governmental aid, totaling to $1.29&nbsp;million (2001&nbsp;USD, $1.5&nbsp;million 2007&nbsp;USD).<ref name="flaid">{{cite web|author=FEMA|year=2001|title=$1.2&nbsp;Million Approved For Florida's Allison Flood Victims|accessdate=2006-06-14|url=http://www.fema.gov/news/newsrelease.fema?id=6016}}</ref> In Pennsylvania, 1,670 flood victims applied for federal aid, totaling to $11.5&nbsp;million (2001&nbsp;USD, $13.4&nbsp;million 2007&nbsp;USD). $3.4&nbsp;million (2001&nbsp;USD, $4&nbsp;million 2007&nbsp;USD) of the total was to replace a [[Southeastern Pennsylvania Transportation Authority|SEPTA]] rail bridge over [[Sandy Run (Wissahickon Creek)|Sandy Run]] in [[Fort Washington, Pennsylvania|Fort Washington]].<ref name="paid">{{cite web|author=FEMA|year=2001|title=Disaster Aid, Loans for Pennsylvanians Near $11.5&nbsp;Million|accessdate=2006-06-14|url=http://www.fema.gov/news/newsrelease.fema?id=5974}}</ref>

===Retirement===
{{seealso|List of retired Atlantic hurricane names}}
Due to extreme destruction, the name Allison was retired in the Spring of 2002, and will never again be used in the [[Atlantic basin]]; the 2001 incarnation of Allison is the only Atlantic tropical system to have its name retired without reaching hurricane strength.  The name was replaced with [[Subtropical Storm Andrea (2007)|Andrea]] in the [[2007 Atlantic hurricane season|2007 season]].
